# assignment-2-camera notes



## Explain the "High-Medium-Low" context of your level design using the provided terminology.

In this context, the level is designed to showcase the tech behind the camera controls.

- On a high level, it features an open space with enough elements to test how the camera behaves in different scenarios. Speed is conveyed by the relative movement to the other objects in the scene. The scale is also conveyed by having an NPC with the same size as the playable character, or massive pillars and a narrow passageway.
- On a medium level, there are only a few assets in the scene and they are placed quite far from each other. Each object serves the purpose of showcasing a different function of the camera controls. The NPC gives a more intimate frame, allowing the player ot focus on a poossible conversation or action. The pillars showcase scale and the passageway can be used to close the camera in a lot and possible trigger a slight sense of claustrophobia.
- On a low level, every time the camera "collides" with certain objects, it zooms in as to avoid having objects between the player and the camera itself. While the player is not manually controlling it, the camer also offsets to the right or left if an object invades the frame on the opposite side.

## Was the camera mechanics intuitive to the player?

- The camera mechanics are quite "usual" in the sense that most games nowadays use the same controls. Right stick controls the camera and if the player is not moving it, then it will auto correct itself to follow the player. One aspect that may not be intuitive could be the inversion of the Y-axis. Some players prefer it inverted, others don't.

## How could the camera mechanics be changed to support the exploration of the level or vice-versa?

- The level could include vistas that in change might be a good excuse to zoom out and slightly focus the camera on them.